# Onshape Webhooks

A webhook is a **standing subscription**: you register a callback `url` plus an
`events[]` list, and Onshape POSTs a JSON notification to that URL whenever a
matching event fires — a model edited, a version created, a translation finished.
It is the push alternative to polling. Webhooks live at the **account/company
level**, not inside a document path (no `did/wid/eid` in the route); scoping to a
single document is done with body fields, not the URL.

## Model

- A webhook is owned by a `user` or `company` and identified by its own
  `webhookid`. The whole group sits under bare `/webhooks` — there is no
  `…/d/{did}/w/{wid}/e/{eid}` path here. You narrow *what* fires by setting
  `documentId` / `companyId` / `filter` in the **registration body**, not the path.
- **Registration → callback loop:** POST `/webhooks` with `url` + `events[]` →
  Onshape stores it → when an event matches, Onshape sends an HTTP POST to your
  `url` carrying a notification payload (the `event`, the webhook `id`, and the
  ids of the affected document/element). Your endpoint must be a **publicly
  reachable HTTPS URL** — localhost won't work for live delivery.
- **Verify / echo:** on registration (and on `POST /webhooks/{webhookid}/ping`)
  Onshape calls your URL to confirm it answers; your endpoint must reply 2xx
  promptly or the webhook is treated as unreachable. Use the **ping** endpoint to
  re-test a callback without waiting for a real event.
- **Event families** (the `events[]` strings, per the slice's `onshape.*`
  namespace):
  - `onshape.model.lifecycle.*` — model-level changes (e.g. a Part Studio /
    Assembly edited or a microversion created).
  - `onshape.document.*` — document-level changes (created, deleted, etc.).
  - `onshape.translation.complete` — an async translation/export job finished.
    This is what pairs with @onshape/export_translation: kick off a translation,
    then get pushed a notification on completion instead of polling the job id.
- `options` (`BTWebhookOptions`) tune delivery — notably **`collapseEvents`**,
  which coalesces a burst of identical events into one notification.
  `isTransient` marks a short-lived subscription; `droppedEventCount` (read on
  GET) reports events Onshape couldn't deliver.

## Endpoints

| METHOD path | purpose |
|---|---|
| `GET /webhooks` | list webhooks registered by a user or company |
| `POST /webhooks` | register a new webhook |
| `GET /webhooks/{webhookid}` | get one webhook's info |
| `POST /webhooks/{webhookid}` | update a webhook |
| `DELETE /webhooks/{webhookid}` | unregister a webhook |
| `POST /webhooks/{webhookid}/ping` | ping a webhook to test its callback |

Query params: `GET /webhooks` takes `company`, `user`, `offset`, `limit`;
`DELETE` takes `blockNotification`.

## Shapes

**Registration request** (`POST /webhooks` — meaningful fields trimmed from the
slice body). `url` + `events` are the core; the rest scope/tune it:

```json
{
  "url": "https://my.app/onshape/hook",
  "events": [
    "onshape.model.lifecycle.changed",
    "onshape.translation.complete"
  ],
  "documentId": "378e93b0ad360aa043a0220b",
  "companyId": "",
  "filter": "",
  "description": "notify my app on model + translation events",
  "options": { "collapseEvents": true },
  "isTransient": false
}
```

**Stored webhook** (response from `POST /webhooks`, `GET /webhooks/{webhookid}`,
and each item of `GET /webhooks`):

```json
{
  "id": "5f...e1",
  "url": "https://my.app/onshape/hook",
  "events": ["onshape.model.lifecycle.changed", "onshape.translation.complete"],
  "companyId": "",
  "description": "notify my app on model + translation events",
  "filter": "",
  "options": { "collapseEvents": true },
  "isTransient": false,
  "droppedEventCount": 0,
  "createdBy": { "id": "...", "name": "..." },
  "createdAt": "2026-06-28T00:00:00Z",
  "modifiedAt": "2026-06-28T00:00:00Z",
  "href": "https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10/webhooks/5f...e1"
}
```

`GET /webhooks` wraps these: `{ "href", "items": [ {…}, … ], "next", "previous" }`.

**Notification Onshape POSTs to your `url`** — per spec, the callback body carries
the fired `event`, the source webhook `id`, and the affected ids (so a
`onshape.translation.complete` notification tells you which translation/document
finished). Echo a 2xx immediately and process asynchronously.

```json
{
  "event": "onshape.translation.complete",
  "webhookId": "5f...e1",
  "documentId": "378e93b0ad360aa043a0220b",
  "workspaceId": "09273312fedee7bf3c3482ad",
  "elementId": "a77918b06d5131918477a269",
  "translationId": "..."
}
```

## Recipe

READ-ONLY listing — safe on any account, returns an empty `items` array on a fresh
one. Basic auth (`access:secret` over HTTPS, local testing only — production uses
HMAC, see @onshape/auth). Creating a webhook needs a **public callback URL**, so
it is not runnable here; the list below is the verify-able read.

```bash
BASE=https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10
AUTH="$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY"

# list every webhook this key's user has registered
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  "$BASE/webhooks" -o hooks.json

# verify: response carries an items[] array (empty is fine for a fresh account)
python3 - <<'PY'
import json
d = json.load(open("hooks.json"))
items = d["items"]
assert isinstance(items, list), "expected an items[] array"
print(f"{len(items)} webhook(s) registered")
for w in items:
    print(w["id"], "->", w["url"], w["events"])
PY
```

To register one (needs a public HTTPS endpoint) and confirm it took, POST the
body from **Shapes** then ping it:

```bash
# create
ID=$(curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -X POST "$BASE/webhooks" \
  --data '{"url":"https://my.app/onshape/hook","events":["onshape.translation.complete"],"options":{"collapseEvents":true}}' \
  | python3 -c 'import sys,json;print(json.load(sys.stdin)["id"])')

# verify the callback answers (Onshape POSTs your url); 2xx body == reachable
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -X POST "$BASE/webhooks/$ID/ping"

# clean up
curl -sf -u "$AUTH" -X DELETE "$BASE/webhooks/$ID"
```

